--- title: "Station Information" author: "Paul S" date: "6/6/24" params: station: "Moonee Ponds" format: html: theme: zephyr fig-width: 6 fig-height: 4 code-fold: false toc: true toc-depth: 4 toc-location: left page-layout: full --- ::: {.cell} ::: ## Information & Overall Scores This page includes information about the seven categories and why they should be considered as factors in priority upzoning: - Zoning suitability - Potential number of new homes - Train service frequency in peak - Train service passenger numbers in peak - Number of local services within a 500m walk - Distance to CBD - Existing transport infrastructure. For Moonee Ponds, the scores are shown below in a summary table. The remainder of this page steps through each factor listed above in no particular order. ::: {.cell} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: Moonee Ponds obtained a final score of 1.76, placing it. ## Service Frequency (why is frequency important?) Service frequency is calculated as the mean number of services per hour in two time periods. The chart below shows: - Number of services between 7 and 10am towards Flinders Street, coloured blue. - Number of services between 4 and 7pm away from Flinders street, coloured green. The chart is also split by direction of travel, which in Melbourne's radial network is either towards or away from Flinders street. The mean values of these two periods are shown as dashed lines, and the mean of those two numbers is the final score. ::: {.cell} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: The morning average freqency is 6.65, the average evening frequency is 6.75, which forms a mean score of 6.7. ## Service Capacity ::: {.cell} ::: This metric aims to measure the amount of space available on trains passing through this station, as there is little point upzoning if there is no capacity to move people. However, for stations in the middle of a train line, passengers will typically continue to board the train until the city. This means that it is not useful to only look at the patronage as trains pass through a given station as more passengers may board later. Instead, it is best to look at the average number of passengers on trains at their last station before the CBD. This gives a better measure of how busy the line itself is overall. Process for Moonee Ponds 1. Find the train line(s) that serve Moonee Ponds: Craigieburn 2. For each train line, find the station nearest to the CBD. These are by definition the same for each line: North Melbourne. 3. For each of these stations just before the CBD, calculate the average patronage of train services at that station, but restrict the search to only train services on the lines identified in step 1. Step 3 is described below, using the target station of North Melbourne. Average passenger counts at North Melbourne across the Craigieburn line(s) are calculated at two times and directions: - Patronage between 7 and 10am towards Flinders Street, denoted as blue in the charts. - Patronage between 4 and 7pm away from Flinders street, shown as green in the charts. The chart is also split by direction of travel, which in Melbourne's radial network is either towards or away from Flinders street. The mean values of these two periods are shown as dashed lines, and the mean of those two numbers is the final score. ::: {.cell} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: The morning average patronage is 424.65, the average evening patronage is 401.36, which forms a mean score of 413. ## Zoning Suitability The number of lots within 1km of stations zoned as either Neighbourhood Residential or General Residential, and NOT under heritage protection is an approximation of 'ease of upzoning' for a given station. The map below shows the properties within 1km of Moonee Ponds that meet the conditions above, shaded in orange. Properties that do not meet the conditions described above are black. Additional information on land use and heritage is provided in tables below the map. ::: {.cell} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: :::{.panel-tabset} ## Key information Out of 4280 lots within 1km radius of Moonee Ponds, 2663 are easiest to upzone. In terms of area, the easiest properties cover 0.5% of the total area of 2.18 km^2. ## Tabular data ::: {.cell} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ::: ## Existing Transport Infrastructure The map below shows tram routes and tram stops in green, as well as bus routes and bus stops in orange. ::: {.cell} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: There are 25 tram stops in a 1km radius, with route(s) 57, 59, 82 servicing the area. For buses, there are 41, with route(s) 404, 476, 472, 477, 506, 469, 508, 510, 483, 467. The data below shows the frequencies per route in both table and bar chart form. :::{.panel-tabset} ## Data ::: {.cell} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ## Chart ::: {.cell} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ::: The final score for 'existing transport infrastructure' is computed by summing the average frequencies of each route and applying a weight to each mode. The current weights are intended to reflect the throughput each mode is capable of. At a minimum, trams can move twice as many people as buses at the same frequency, so trams are weighted twice as much as buses. The final score is 86.17. ## Capacity Delta Zoned capacity is a measure of how many dwellings could fit in an area, given the current zoning. It is a theoretic maximum. This section looks at the current zoned capacity, and compares it to a theoretic zoned capacity under 'Missing Middle' zoning. To reiterate, the potential future zoned capacity is **a theoretic maximum**, and extremely unlikely to be realised if upzoning occured. ::: {.cell} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: :::
